<main class="content">

  <p>After someone dies, their estate typically takes 9 to 18 months to fully settle. During this time, beneficiaries wait — often unable to access funds, sell property, or move forward.</p>

  <h2>Why Does Probate Take So Long?</h2>

  <p>Several factors contribute to probate delays:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Court processing times</strong> — Probate applications take 4-12 weeks just to be granted</li>
    <li><strong>Asset identification</strong> — Locating and valuing all assets takes time</li>
    <li><strong>Creditor notification periods</strong> — Executors must wait for potential claims</li>
    <li><strong>Tax clearances</strong> — Final tax returns and clearances from the ATO</li>
    <li><strong>Property sales</strong> — Real estate can take months to sell</li>
    <li><strong>Disputes</strong> — Any challenge to the will adds months or years</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What Causes the Longest Delays?</h2>

  <p>The biggest delays typically come from:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Missing or unclear wills</strong> — Courts must determine validity</li>
    <li><strong>Family disputes</strong> — Contested wills can take years to resolve</li>
    <li><strong>Complex assets</strong> — Businesses, trusts, or overseas property</li>
    <li><strong>Executor issues</strong> — Inexperienced, unavailable, or conflicted executors</li>
    <li><strong>Incomplete records</strong> — Missing documents, unknown accounts</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="cta-box">
    <h3>The Real Impact</h3>
    <p>During probate, beneficiaries often cannot access inherited funds. Mortgages still need paying. Bills accumulate. Families who expected quick access to inheritance find themselves waiting months — sometimes over a year.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>How to Speed Up Probate</h2>

  <p>While you can't eliminate probate, good planning can significantly reduce delays:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Keep your will updated and professionally prepared</li>
    <li>Maintain organised records of all assets and accounts</li>
    <li>Choose an executor who is capable and available</li>
    <li>Consider professional executor support for complex estates</li>
    <li>Communicate your wishes to reduce potential disputes</li>
    <li>Use binding death benefit nominations for superannuation</li>
  </ul>

